You’re pointing at something real: modern conflict often looks less like tanks at the gate and more like pressure on the systems a society depends on.

⸻

🧱 What “modern siege” looks like

Instead of surrounding walls, pressure targets infrastructure and connectivity:
	•	Energy (power grids, fuel supply)
	•	Communications (internet backbones, satellites, cables)
	•	Logistics (ports, rail, trucking, payment rails)
	•	Data systems (banking, healthcare records, control systems)

Disrupt enough of these at once and daily life degrades quickly—sometimes without a single frontline moving.

⸻

🧠 The information layer (where your point about AI fits)

There’s a parallel track alongside physical disruption:
	•	Rumors, propaganda, and deepfakes can spread faster than facts
	•	AI can scale both good and bad content, making it harder to sort signal from noise
	•	Confusion can lead to panic buying, bank runs, or loss of trust in institutions

So it’s less “AI alone ruins a country” and more:

Infrastructure strain + information confusion = amplified instability

⸻

⚖️ Important balance
	•	States are resilient. Redundancy, backups, and human judgment matter a lot.
	•	Information doesn’t automatically equal collapse. People, institutions, and checks (journalism, verification, community networks) counterbalance it.
	•	The biggest risk is erosion of trust, not just damage to hardware.

⸻

🧩 Clean framing

**Modern siege = pressure on systems (energy, logistics, comms)
	•	pressure on perception (information environment).**

Either one alone is manageable. Together, they can compound.

⸻

🛡️ What actually helps societies hold up
	•	Redundancy (multiple power/comm pathways)
	•	Clear, trusted communication from credible sources
	•	Media literacy (people verifying before reacting)
	•	Local resilience (communities that can function if systems degrade)

⸻

🔧 Bottom line

You’re right that the battlefield has widened:

It’s not just about territory anymore—it’s about systems and trust.

And the fastest collapses don’t come from a single tool (like AI), but from stacked pressures hitting both at once.